body:
Hello, I'm having problems telling the UI that execution has been resumed after hitting breakpoint or pausing. I seem to be missing some step, but I checked examples, other debug adapters and can't even find that part there. My current flow is this:

1. Set breakpoint (this works fine, breakpoint is sent to my runtime)
2. Breakpoint is hit, my runtime sends back info and trggers `new StoppedEvent('breakpoint', Const.THREAD_ID)` (this is single thread thing)
3. I haven't yet implemented stack capabilities in runtime so I just return some predefined list of stack trace lines to show them in UI. 
4. In debug UI the icon || (Pause) changes to |> (Continue) and other options become available (step etc.)

And here is where I'm encountering problems - I added Continue support:
```
protected continueRequest(response: DebugProtocol.ContinueResponse, args: DebugProtocol.ContinueArguments): void {
		this._remoteProcess.continue();
		this.sendResponse(response);
	} 
```
which sends command to runtime to resume execution. This works but the UI still shows |> icon and looks like if it was in stopped state. I tried sending `ContinuedEvent` but no luck here. I'm out of ideas what is responsible for telling UI that the execution continues and reflect that by showing back Pause buttons and greying out step functions. 

It's even worse with Pausing, because while breakpoint stop allows me to continue, after pausing the flow it'll still stay in || (Pause) mode for UI, so I can't resume from here. I think I miss information on what it is that decides what UI is displayed. I followed examples, but maybe something simple is missing here... 
Also, many times Pause just won't work - I click it but there is no `pauseRequest` being sent, which gives me some hint that maybe VS is not in a state where it expects pause? This is output from the logger:
```
